#' UCI Wine Quality Dataset: Red Wines
#'
#' Physicochemical properties and quality ratings for 1,599 red wines from
#' the Vinho Verde region of Portugal. This dataset is commonly used for
#' regression and classification tasks in machine learning.
#'
#' @format A data frame with 1,599 observations and 12 variables:
#' \describe{
#'   \item{fixed_acidity}{Fixed acidity (tartaric acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{volatile_acidity}{Volatile acidity (acetic acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{citric_acid}{Citric acid (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{residual_sugar}{Residual sugar (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{chlorides}{Chlorides (sodium chloride, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{free_sulfur_dioxide}{Free sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{total_sulfur_dioxide}{Total sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{density}{Density (g/cm³)}
#'   \item{pH}{pH value}
#'   \item{sulphates}{Sulphates (potassium sulphate, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{alcohol}{Alcohol content (% by volume)}
#'   \item{quality}{Quality score (integer from 0 to 10, based on sensory data)}
#' }
#'
#' @details
#' The input variables are based on physicochemical tests. The output variable
#' `quality` is based on the median of at least three evaluations by wine
#' experts, who rated the wine on a scale from 0 (very bad) to 10 (excellent).
#' In practice, the observed quality scores range from 3 to 8.
#'
#' All physicochemical variables are continuous. The 11 input features provide
#' a moderately high-dimensional space for exploring dimension reduction
#' techniques.
#'
#' @source
#' UCI Machine Learning Repository:
#' \url{https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality}
#'
#' @references
#' Cortez, P., Cerdeira, A., Almeida, F., Matos, T., & Reis, J. (2009).
#' Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties.
#' \emph{Decision Support Systems}, 47(4), 547--553.
#' \doi{10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016}
#'
#' @examples
#' data(wine_red)
#' dim(wine_red)
#' summary(wine_red$quality)
#'
#' # Correlation matrix of physicochemical properties
#' cor_mat <- cor(wine_red[, 1:11])
#' round(cor_mat[1:5, 1:5], 2)
"wine_red"


#' UCI Wine Quality Dataset: White Wines
#'
#' Physicochemical properties and quality ratings for 4,898 white wines from
#' the Vinho Verde region of Portugal. This dataset is commonly used for
#' regression and classification tasks in machine learning.
#'
#' @format A data frame with 4,898 observations and 12 variables:
#' \describe{
#'   \item{fixed_acidity}{Fixed acidity (tartaric acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{volatile_acidity}{Volatile acidity (acetic acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{citric_acid}{Citric acid (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{residual_sugar}{Residual sugar (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{chlorides}{Chlorides (sodium chloride, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{free_sulfur_dioxide}{Free sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{total_sulfur_dioxide}{Total sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{density}{Density (g/cm³)}
#'   \item{pH}{pH value}
#'   \item{sulphates}{Sulphates (potassium sulphate, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{alcohol}{Alcohol content (% by volume)}
#'   \item{quality}{Quality score (integer from 0 to 10, based on sensory data)}
#' }
#'
#' @details
#' The input variables are based on physicochemical tests. The output variable
#' `quality` is based on the median of at least three evaluations by wine
#' experts, who rated the wine on a scale from 0 (very bad) to 10 (excellent).
#' In practice, the observed quality scores range from 3 to 9.
#'
#' The white wine dataset is larger than the red wine dataset (4,898 vs 1,599
#' observations), reflecting the higher production of white wines in the
#' Vinho Verde region.
#'
#' @source
#' UCI Machine Learning Repository:
#' \url{https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality}
#'
#' @references
#' Cortez, P., Cerdeira, A., Almeida, F., Matos, T., & Reis, J. (2009).
#' Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties.
#' \emph{Decision Support Systems}, 47(4), 547--553.
#' \doi{10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016}
#'
#' @examples
#' data(wine_white)
#' dim(wine_white)
#' summary(wine_white$quality)
"wine_white"


#' UCI Wine Quality Dataset: Combined Red and White Wines
#'
#' Combined dataset of red and white wines from the Vinho Verde region,
#' with an additional factor variable indicating wine type. Useful for
#' classification problems distinguishing red from white wines based on
#' physicochemical properties.
#'
#' @format A data frame with 6,497 observations and 13 variables:
#' \describe{
#'   \item{fixed_acidity}{Fixed acidity (tartaric acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{volatile_acidity}{Volatile acidity (acetic acid, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{citric_acid}{Citric acid (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{residual_sugar}{Residual sugar (g/dm³)}
#'   \item{chlorides}{Chlorides (sodium chloride, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{free_sulfur_dioxide}{Free sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{total_sulfur_dioxide}{Total sulfur dioxide (mg/dm³)}
#'   \item{density}{Density (g/cm³)}
#'   \item{pH}{pH value}
#'   \item{sulphates}{Sulphates (potassium sulphate, g/dm³)}
#'   \item{alcohol}{Alcohol content (% by volume)}
#'   \item{quality}{Quality score (integer from 0 to 10, based on sensory data)}
#'   \item{type}{Wine type: factor with levels "red" and "white"}
#' }
#'
#' @details
#' This combined dataset enables classification tasks where the goal is to
#' predict wine type from physicochemical properties. The two classes are
#' imbalanced: approximately 75\% white wines and 25\% red wines.
#'
#' The dataset is particularly useful for illustrating Linear Discriminant
#' Analysis (LDA), as the classification problem is relatively easy---red
#' and white wines have notably different chemical profiles, especially in
#' total sulfur dioxide and volatile acidity.
#'
#' @seealso [wine_red], [wine_white]
#'
#' @source
#' UCI Machine Learning Repository:
#' \url{https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality}
#'
#' @references
#' Cortez, P., Cerdeira, A., Almeida, F., Matos, T., & Reis, J. (2009).
#' Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties.
#' \emph{Decision Support Systems}, 47(4), 547--553.
#' \doi{10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016}
#'
#' @examples
#' data(wine_quality)
#' table(wine_quality$type)
#'
#' # LDA to classify wine type
#' library(MASS)
#' lda_fit <- lda(type ~ . - quality, data = wine_quality)
#' lda_pred <- predict(lda_fit)
#' table(Predicted = lda_pred$class, Actual = wine_quality$type)
"wine_quality"
